### Phantom Types for Type Safety

Phantom types are generic type parameters that don't appear in runtime values. They exist only at compile-time to enforce type constraints. This pattern is powerful for creating type-safe wrappers that disappear after compilation.

Phantom types help track state or capabilities without adding runtime cost. You can enforce invariants like 'this value is validated' or 'this operation is authorized' purely through the type system.

typescript
type Brand<T, B> = T & { readonly __brand: B };
type ValidatedEmail = Brand<string, 'ValidatedEmail'>;
type UserId = Brand<number, 'UserId'>;

function validateEmail(email: string): ValidatedEmail {
  if (!email.includes('@')) throw new Error('Invalid');
  return email as ValidatedEmail;
}

function sendEmail(to: ValidatedEmail) {
  console.log(`Sending to ${to}`);
}

const email = validateEmail('user@example.com');
sendEmail(email);


**Common interview trap:** Candidates often forget that phantom types must be enforceable—the validation function must be the only way to create the branded type, otherwise the guarantee is worthless.

