### Advanced Infer Patterns

The `infer` keyword in conditional types allows pattern matching on types. You can extract parts of complex types and use them in the result. This enables powerful type transformations without runtime overhead.

Infer works left-to-right and is greedy by default. You can use multiple infers to destructure nested structures, including function signatures, array elements, and promise values.

typescript
type Flatten<T> = T extends Array<infer U> ? U : T;
type FlattenDeep<T> = T extends Array<infer U> 
  ? FlattenDeep<U> 
  : T;

type Params<T> = T extends (...args: infer P) => any ? P : never;
type ReturnType<T> = T extends (...args: any) => infer R ? R : never;

type Awaited<T> = T extends Promise<infer U> ? U : T;

function fn(x: string, y: number): boolean { return true; }
type FnParams = Params<typeof fn>; // [string, number]
type FnReturn = ReturnType<typeof fn>; // boolean
type Unwrapped = Awaited<Promise<string>>; // string


**Common interview trap:** Candidates use `infer` in simple cases but struggle when nesting multiple infers or dealing with distributive conditional types in unions.

